      Sculptor
   =20
 =20
Here=E2=80=99s the classic life cycle of a hedge fund. You quit your job at=
 Goldman Sachs Group Inc., or at someone else=E2=80=99s hedge fund, and you=
 start a new fund with some of your own savings and some=C2=A0money from yo=
ur former clients, bosses, etc. You charge a management fee of 2% of assets=
, which you use to pay for rent and Bloomberg terminals and stuff, and a pe=
rformance fee of 20% of profits, which you use to pay bonuses to a couple o=
f analysts and a bigger bonus to yourself. Living, as you do, on performanc=
e fees, you care a lot about performance, and you perform well. This has tw=
o=C2=A0effects: (1) you attract more clients who like the performance and (=
2) you pay yourself large bonuses out of your large performance fees.=C2=A0=
The former effect tends to increase the size of your fund=C2=A0while reduci=
ng=C2=A0your percentage ownership (more outside money), while the latter te=
nds to increase your percentage ownership (you pay yourself more than you c=
an spend and, as a matter of course, keep your savings in the fund).If you =
continue this way for a while, and performance remains good, then your fund=
 will grow and eventually you will reach some capacity cap where you run a =
lot of money and don=E2=80=99t want any more. Investors will come to you be=
gging to put in more money and you will say no. You will close your fund to=
 new investors, maybe you=E2=80=99ll start handing money back to old invest=
ors, maybe you=E2=80=99ll increase your fees. This will all tend to increas=
e your percentage ownership of the fund. Eventually, if all goes well, you =
will return all the outside money and have like a $20 billion family office=
 where you run only your money and keep 100% of the profits.=C2=A0If all go=
es less well then investors will demand their money back due to underperfor=
mance before you have a chance to send it back to them due to overperforman=
ce. If this happens in the right order =E2=80=94=C2=A0first you do well and=
 accumulate billions of dollars of your own,=C2=A0then=C2=A0you do poorly =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0then it looks a lot like the good result; you complain more =
about investor disloyalty but also end up running your own multibillion-dol=
lar family office. If it happens in the wrong order =E2=80=94=C2=A0you do p=
oorly first =E2=80=94=C2=A0then they all take their money back, there=E2=80=
=99s not enough left to bother with, you close the fund and you go back to =
having a job at a bank or someone else=E2=80=99s hedge fund.This model lack=
s a succession plan. The goal, in this model, is not to build an enduring i=
nstitution that will carry on without you, steadily accumulating client ass=
ets for generations. The goal is to use outside capital to generate your ow=
n vast wealth, and then get rid of the outside capital to focus on managing=
 your own vast wealth. So you are not really looking for some young whipper=
snapper to succeed you; you are not dreaming of one day handing the pool of=
 capital over to your handpicked prot=C3=A9g=C3=A9. That capital is yours! =
You hire young whippersnappers, sure, and mentor them, and if they perform =
well you pay them well, and once you=E2=80=99ve paid them well for a while =
they accumulate enough money to leave and start their own hedge fund, which=
 you seed with some of your own (fund=E2=80=99s, family office=E2=80=99s) c=
apital. But they don=E2=80=99t get to take over your fund, because that fun=
d is yours.This is not, of course, the only model. You can try to build an =
institution; you can even become a public company. Stuff  can get weird tho=
ugh:Jimmy Levin=E2=80=99s rise to the top of Sculptor Capital Management In=
c. was accompanied by eye-popping pay packages. For one director, the sums =
became too much.=C2=A0J. Morgan Rutman quit the hedge fund firm=E2=80=99s b=
oard this week, decrying governance failures at Dan Och=E2=80=99s former co=
mpany -- which include what he said could be an annual payout of almost $20=
0 million to Levin. He also claimed that he was frozen out of the compensat=
ion process, suggesting it was because he opposed Levin=E2=80=99s package.=
=C2=A0You can read this story as one of excessive executive compensation at=
 a public company, but there is another available=C2=A0reading. That Bloomb=
erg article goes on:But Rutman wasn=E2=80=99t a typical board member: he wa=
s the sole representative chosen by Och, who is still Sculptor=E2=80=99s la=
rgest shareholder. The billionaire, who stepped away in 2019, passed over h=
is former protege Levin when he left, instead handing his company to an out=
sider.=C2=A0Och, 61, now runs his own family office, Willoughby Capital. Ru=
tman, who=E2=80=99s president of Willoughby, joined Sculptor=E2=80=99s boar=
d in 2019 and served on the compensation committee.=C2=A0This is a story ab=
out Dan Och, who left Goldman to start a hedge fund called Och-Ziff Capital=
 Management, which became one of the biggest hedge funds. It got so big tha=
t he took the management company public in 2007, but it was so much his hed=
ge fund that (1) his name was on it and (2) he hired=C2=A0his children=E2=
=80=99s summer-camp water-skiing instructor=C2=A0to be an investor at the f=
und. Really a classic =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s a pile of money with my name =
on it=E2=80=9D move.=C2=A0But then through some combination of (1) Och bein=
g too rich to manage outside money full time, (2) the water-skiing instruct=
or, Jimmy Levin, turning out to be by all accounts an exceptionally talente=
d (and lucky) investor, (3) Levin also apparently being rather a tough nego=
tiator for himself and (4) public-company governance structures being somew=
hat less deferential to Och than a private pile of money would be, Och-Ziff=
 became the more neutrally named Sculptor, Och left and Levin =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0after a power struggle in which Och briefly installed someone else =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0became chief executive officer and chief investment officer.And=
 Levin is now in the unusual=C2=A0position of=C2=A0running a gigantic ($37.=
9 billion) hedge fund without being the billionaire owner of, like, half th=
e money in the=C2=A0fund. Instead he is the chief executive officer of a pu=
blic hedge-fund firm with an equity market capitalization of about $1 billi=
on, who is paid mostly in management-company stock by a public company with=
 a compensation committee of independent directors. CEOs of $1 billion mark=
et-cap firms, as a rule, do not get nine-digit pay packages. On the other h=
and every year  we talk about=C2=A0rankings of =E2=80=9Chighest paid hedge =
fund managers,=E2=80=9D whose =E2=80=9Cpay=E2=80=9D (1) consists mostly of =
the appreciation of their own stakes in their funds and (2) has 10 digits. =
As the CEO of a $1 billion public company, Levin is comically overpaid; as =
the=C2=A0manager of a $30+ billion hedge fund with good performance, he is =
getting way, way, way less than his peers. Of course most of the people=C2=
=A0running $30+ billion hedge funds are running a lot of their own money, t=
hough, which makes the comparison hard.Here is Rutman=E2=80=99s letter of c=
omplaint, which specifically cites those lists of =E2=80=9Chighest paid hed=
ge fund managers=E2=80=9D as a source of Levin=E2=80=99s comp:First, the Co=
mpensation Committee recommended, and the Board approved, Mr. Levin=E2=80=
=99s compensation package despite Semler Brossy=E2=80=99s warning that even=
 under a conservative =E2=80=9Cbase=E2=80=9D scenario, Mr. Levin would rece=
ive an =E2=80=9Camortized total compensation level of $94.3 million per yea=
r, [which] is exceedingly rare across general industry=E2=80=9D and could o=
nly be deemed reasonable in the asset management industry if compared to th=
e annual gains of the world=E2=80=99s highest paid private alternative asse=
t managers (much of which are likely to reflect the gains in their own inve=
stments in the funds, rather than Board-awarded compensation). =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0The deck distributed shortly in advance of the Board meeting reflects th=
at the principal =E2=80=9Ccompetitive=E2=80=9D justification for the pay pa=
ckage was the representation that it would =E2=80=9Censure competitive comp=
ensation within the private market hedge fund industry=E2=80=9D because the=
 =E2=80=9C[t]op 25 hedge fund managers [have been] paid on average $200m to=
 $2.7bn since 2009,=E2=80=9D and the CIO of Blackrock=E2=80=99s hedge fund =
reportedly =E2=80=9Cearned a nine-figure sum,=E2=80=9D in the prior year.An=
d:Third, the Board approved an award of equity to Mr. Levin that would brin=
g his pro-forma share/unit holdings to approximately 12.5 million shares/un=
its, representing approximately 20.7 % of all outstanding shares. =E2=80=A6=
 The equity interest in Sculptor that the Board has now granted Mr. Levin e=
xceeds that of even the founders of asset management firms that are =E2=80=
=9Csignificantly larger than Sculptor=E2=80=9D - - Apollo, Ares, Blackstone=
, and KKR. Of course, Mr. Levin is not a founder of Sculptor and his signif=
icant equity stake is the result of compensation awards, not his creation o=
f the firm.That=E2=80=99s all true but if they just gave him 100% of the eq=
uity in the management company he=E2=80=99d still be a little light compare=
d to the other people running $30+ billion hedge funds. Most of the people =
who have ended up in charge of $30+=C2=A0billion hedge funds will make a bi=
llion dollars if their fund has a good year, not because a compensation com=
mittee voted them a billion-dollar paycheck but because they have, over the=
 years of running the fund=C2=A0they founded, accrued billions of dollars o=
f investments in the fund, and when the fund goes up so does their wealth. =
If you bring in a new guy you have to either (1) get him to accept a differ=
ent model, one that involves him being much less rich than the heads of com=
petitor firms, or (2) throw tons of money at him to catch him up.=C2=A0
