      Here are the customers=E2=80=99 yachts
   =20
 =20
Credit Suisse Group AG lends a lot of money to a lot of different customers=
 for a lot of different things. If you want undifferentiated diversified ex=
posure to all of those different loans, you can buy Credit Suisse stock (wh=
ich gives you risky equity exposure)=C2=A0or bonds (safer senior exposure),=
 or deposit your money at Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s bank (very safe super-sen=
ior exposure).Or you can skip all the mortgages, small-business loans, corp=
orate lines of credit etc., and buy direct exposure to only the finest hand=
picked yacht loans. The Financial Times reports:Credit Suisse has securitis=
ed a portfolio of loans linked to its wealthiest customers=E2=80=99 yachts =
and private jets, in an unusual use of derivatives to offload risks associa=
ted with lending to ultra-rich oligarchs and entrepreneurs.The Swiss lender=
, which has endured a bruising year marked by repeated scandal, quietly sol=
d on a slice of the risk related to $2bn of its =E2=80=9Cultra-high-net-wor=
th=E2=80=9D client loans at the end of 2021.The securitisation of the portf=
olio of loans to tycoons and oligarchs backed by their =E2=80=9Cjets, yacht=
s, real estate and/or financial assets=E2=80=9D was made by a unit of the b=
ank that has previously been plagued with sanctions-related issues.An inves=
tor presentation for the deal, seen by the Financial Times, explains that o=
ne of the main goals of this division is to =E2=80=9Ccreate a positive bran=
d impression of CS by financing the principals=E2=80=99 favourite business =
tools (business jet) and luxury toys (yachts)=E2=80=9D. =E2=80=A6The nature=
 of the underlying collateral meant Credit Suisse had to offer an eye-water=
ing interest rate of more than 11 per cent to entice a handful of hedge fun=
ds into the $80mn transaction, an indication of the price the bank was will=
ing to pay to improve its capital position without tapping public equity ma=
rkets.One way to think about this is that if Credit Suisse is carving out i=
ts oligarch yacht loans to sell their credit exposure to hedge funds, then =
the hedge funds value the yacht loans more highly than public shareholders =
do.[1] Like,=C2=A0you can go to hedge fund managers and say =E2=80=9Chey do=
 you want to own the equity tranche of our oligarch yacht loans=E2=80=9D an=
d the hedge fund managers will say =E2=80=9Cahahaha that=E2=80=99s awesome =
I=E2=80=99m in for $10 million,=E2=80=9D and at the same time you can go to=
 your regulators and shareholders and say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve moved the =
oligarch yacht loans off our books, now if the oligarch yacht loans default=
 our shareholders and depositors will not be on the hook=E2=80=9D and the s=
hareholders and regulators will say =E2=80=9Cah what a relief, we don=E2=80=
=99t want any oligarch yacht loans.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The world of bank capital=
 relief and significant risk transfer trades can be pretty abstract, and I =
have written admiringly=C2=A0about Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s efforts to make =
it more so. Credit Suisse has, among other things,=C2=A0sold the credit ris=
k of its derivatives to its managing directors=E2=80=99 bonus pool, and sol=
d its rogue trading risk=C2=A0to some bondholders.But it is worth saying th=
at=C2=A0this=C2=A0trade is extremely intuitive. Credit Suisse wants to be i=
n the business of financing oligarchs=E2=80=99 yachts, because (1) this enc=
ourages the oligarchs to do more business with Credit Suisse and (2) there =
is a certain sort of branding halo, for a Swiss bank, to be able to say =E2=
=80=9Coh of course we do a lot of oligarch yacht financing.=E2=80=9D But if=
 there=E2=80=99s ever a wave of defaults on oligarch yacht loans and Credit=
 Suisse runs into trouble with its capital levels, it will have to call its=
 regulators and say =E2=80=9Chey we are low on capital=E2=80=9D and the reg=
ulators will say =E2=80=9Cwhat happened=E2=80=9D and Credit Suisse will hav=
e to say =E2=80=9Cthe oligarch yachts sank=E2=80=9D and the regulators will=
 be=C2=A0really=C2=A0mad. Like, =E2=80=9Cbank loses money due to housing do=
wnturn=E2=80=9D is fine, as these things go. =E2=80=9CBank loses money due =
to being slow on the trigger with concentrated margin loans=E2=80=9D  is no=
t great. But =E2=80=9Cbank loses money due to oligarch yacht loans=E2=80=9D=
 is terrible! Terrible! You can=E2=80=99t do that!So you do a trade where C=
redit Suisse makes the oligarch yacht loans, for branding and relationship =
and business development purposes, and as far as the oligarchs are concerne=
d it is a leading, generous, flexible, commercial provider of yacht loans. =
But then it sells the default risk of the oligarch yacht loans to people wh=
o have a sense of humor about=C2=A0oligarch yacht loan risk, because bank r=
egulators absolutely do not. For 11%,=C2=A0surely some hedge funds do.I do =
hope that when they close this deal they invite all the hedge fund managers=
 who bought it, and all the oligarchs whose yachts it helped finance, to a =
party on one of the yachts. I feel like they could probably get a break on =
the rate if they did=C2=A0that.
