      Web3 economics
   =20
 =20
My basic model of Web3 is that any Web3 project consists of (1) the ostensi=
ble=C2=A0project=C2=A0plus=C2=A0(2) a Ponzi scheme. (We have discussed this=
 mainly  here and  here.) If you do a thing in a Web3 project, you get some=
 tokens, and then if more people do it the tokens become more valuable; you=
 are rewarded for doing the thing to the extent that new investors put mone=
y in after you. Mostly this strikes me as bad! However! If you take a worth=
y but not especially sexy distributed project and add, like,=C2=A0a little =
bit=C2=A0of Ponzi to it, maybe that is something? At the New York Times, Ke=
vin Roose writes about Helium:On a basic level, Helium is a decentralized w=
ireless network for =E2=80=9Cinternet of things=E2=80=9D devices, powered b=
y cryptocurrency.The network is made up of devices called Helium hot spots,=
 gadgets with antennas that can send small amounts of data over long distan=
ces using radio frequencies. These hot spots, which cost roughly $500 apiec=
e and can reach 200 times farther than conventional Wi-Fi hot spots, share =
their owners=E2=80=99 bandwidth with nearby internet-connected devices =E2=
=80=94 like parking meters, air-quality sensors or smart kitchen appliances=
.Anyone can use the Helium network, although most of its users so far are c=
ompanies like Lime (which has used Helium to keep tabs on its connected sco=
oters) and the Victor mousetrap company (which uses it for a new line of in=
ternet-connected traps).=C2=A0=E2=80=A6Helium, which was founded in 2013, d=
idn=E2=80=99t start off as a crypto company. Its founders originally tried =
to build a long-range, peer-to-peer wireless network the old-fashioned way =
=E2=80=94 by persuading people and businesses to set up hot spots and strin=
ging them together. But they struggled to get enough participants, and the =
network stalled. =E2=80=A6So the company tore up its old business model and=
 settled on a new one. Instead of building its network itself, Helium would=
 make it fully decentralized and let users build it themselves by buying an=
d connecting their own hot spots. Participants would be paid in crypto toke=
ns, and they=E2=80=99d get to vote on proposed ideas for changes to the net=
work. If the price of those tokens rose, they=E2=80=99d make even more mone=
y, and set up even more hot spots.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThis,=E2=80=9D writes Roos=
e, =E2=80=9Cis one of crypto=E2=80=99s superpowers =E2=80=94 the ability to=
 kick-start projects by providing an incentive to get in on the ground floo=
r.=E2=80=9D The more people who join the project after you, the more money =
you make. Ordinarily a network benefits from network effects, and you shoul=
d join a network that a lot of people already use. But crypto networks bene=
fit from =E2=80=9Ctoken=C2=A0effects,=E2=80=9D and you should join a networ=
k that a lot of people=C2=A0will use in the future. There is some guesswork=
 involved there of course, and some incentive=C2=A0for hype. (=E2=80=9CA ca=
rdinal rule of Helium=E2=80=99s 140,000-member Discord chat server is that =
you=E2=80=99re not allowed to discuss token prices,=E2=80=9D notes Roose, w=
hich should reduce hype.)Here it seems fine, sure, why not. I do not know a=
 ton about Helium. It is plausible that, without the financial innovation o=
f crypto tokenomics,=C2=A0the world would be under-provided with internet-c=
onnected mousetraps and scooters. (I kid! I=E2=80=99m sure it=E2=80=99s goo=
d.) It=E2=80=99s just, you know, this basic approach is somewhat independen=
t of=C2=A0the value of the underlying project, and can work=C2=A0with thing=
s that are less socially beneficial than internet-connected mousetraps.=C2=
=A0Elsewhere here is Ian Bogost on Web3: =E2=80=9CThe Internet Is Just Inve=
stment Banking Now.=E2=80=9D
