      This again
   =20
 =20
I don=E2=80=99t really envy  the SEC here:Tesla Inc. received another subpo=
ena from the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission about a subject that k=
eeps coming up: Elon Musk=E2=80=99s tweeting in 2018 that he was considerin=
g taking the carmaker private.The SEC issued the subpoena on Nov. 16, seeki=
ng information about Tesla=E2=80=99s governance processes and compliance wi=
th the settlement reached with the agency in September 2018, the company sa=
id in a regulatory filing. Tesla agreed to put in place controls to oversee=
 Musk=E2=80=99s communications -- including his tweets -- after the SEC all=
eged the chief executive officer committed securities fraud by saying he ha=
d secured funding for the company to go private.Do you think that Tesla law=
yers=C2=A0are reviewing Elon Musk=E2=80=99s tweets before he tweets them? N=
o, they are not, as you can tell by the fact that  Musk said as much during=
 a television interview in which he also said =E2=80=9CI want to be clear. =
I do not respect the SEC. I do not respect them.=E2=80=9D And the SEC previ=
ously  sued Musk for this =E2=80=94=C2=A0not for the original 2018 tweet, I=
 mean, but for subsequently not having lawyers review the tweets =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and Musk went on Twitter to make fun of them some more, and eventuall=
y the SEC and Musk sort of agreed to disagree. But there is still, technica=
lly, an amended settlement in place in which Musk has to run certain catego=
ries of tweets by Tesla lawyers, and the SEC somehow can=E2=80=99t help its=
elf and wants to know if Musk is complying with that settlement. The correc=
t answer is =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t ask!=E2=80=9D
