<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Sculptor</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s the classic life cycle =
of a hedge fund. You quit your job at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., or at someo=
ne else=E2=80=99s hedge fund, and you start a new fund with some of your ow=
n savings and some=C2=A0money from your former clients, bosses, etc. You ch=
arge a management fee of 2% of assets, which you use to pay for rent and Bl=
oomberg terminals and stuff, and a performance fee of 20% of profits, which=
 you use to pay bonuses to a couple of analysts and a bigger bonus to yours=
elf. Living, as you do, on performance fees, you care a lot about performan=
ce, and you perform well. This has two=C2=A0effects: (1) you attract more c=
lients who like the performance and (2) you pay yourself large bonuses out =
of your large performance fees.=C2=A0The former effect tends to increase th=
e size of your fund=C2=A0while reducing=C2=A0your percentage ownership (mor=
e outside money), while the latter tends to increase your percentage owners=
hip (you pay yourself more than you can spend and, as a matter of course, k=
eep your savings in the fund).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you conti=
nue this way for a while, and performance remains good, then your fund will=
 grow and eventually you will reach some capacity cap where you run a lot o=
f money and don=E2=80=99t want any more. Investors will come to you begging=
 to put in more money and you will say no. You will close your fund to new =
investors, maybe you=E2=80=99ll start handing money back to old investors, =
maybe you=E2=80=99ll increase your fees. This will all tend to increase you=
r percentage ownership of the fund. Eventually, if all goes well, you will =
return all the outside money and have like a $20 billion family office wher=
e you run only your money and keep 100% of the profits.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If all goes less well then investors will demand their=
 money back due to underperformance before you have a chance to send it bac=
k to them due to overperformance. If this happens in the right order =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0first you do well and accumulate billions of dollars of your own,=
=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>you do poorly =E2=80=94=C2=A0then it looks a lot l=
ike the good result; you complain more about investor disloyalty but also e=
nd up running your own multibillion-dollar family office. If it happens in =
the wrong order =E2=80=94=C2=A0you do poorly first =E2=80=94=C2=A0then they=
 all take their money back, there=E2=80=99s not enough left to bother with,=
 you close the fund and you go back to having a job at a bank or someone el=
se=E2=80=99s hedge fund.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This model lacks a=
 succession plan. The goal, in this model, is not to build an enduring inst=
itution that will carry on without you, steadily accumulating client assets=
 for generations. The goal is to use outside capital to generate your own v=
ast wealth, and then get rid of the outside capital to focus on managing yo=
ur own vast wealth. So you are not really looking for some young whippersna=
pper to succeed you; you are not dreaming of one day handing the pool of ca=
pital over to your handpicked prot=C3=A9g=C3=A9. That capital is yours! You=
 hire young whippersnappers, sure, and mentor them, and if they perform wel=
l you pay them well, and once you=E2=80=99ve paid them well for a while the=
y accumulate enough money to leave and start their own hedge fund, which yo=
u seed with some of your own (fund=E2=80=99s, family office=E2=80=99s) capi=
tal. But they don=E2=80=99t get to take over your fund, because that fund i=
s yours.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not, of course, the only m=
odel. You can try to build an institution; you can even become a public com=
pany. Stuff <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/266267=
31.270615/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItM=
DMvc2N1bHB0b3ItYm9hcmQtbWVtYmVyLXJ1dG1hbi1xdWl0cy1jaXRpbmctZXhjZXNzaXZlLWNl=
by1wYXk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB51422d22" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> can get weird though</a>:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jimmy Levin=E2=80=99s rise to the top=
 of Sculptor Capital Management Inc. was accompanied by eye-popping pay pac=
kages. For one director, the sums became too much.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">J. Morgan Rutman quit the hedge fund firm=E2=80=99s board thi=
s week, decrying governance failures at Dan Och=E2=80=99s former company --=
 which include what he said could be an annual payout of almost $200 millio=
n to Levin. He also claimed that he was frozen out of the compensation proc=
ess, suggesting it was because he opposed Levin=E2=80=99s package.=C2=A0</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can read this story as one o=
f excessive executive compensation at a public company, but there is anothe=
r available=C2=A0reading. That Bloomberg article goes on:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Rutman wasn=E2=80=99t a typical board member=
: he was the sole representative chosen by Och, who is still Sculptor=E2=80=
=99s largest shareholder. The billionaire, who stepped away in 2019, passed=
 over his former protege Levin when he left, instead handing his company to=
 an outsider.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Och, 61, now runs his o=
wn family office, Willoughby Capital. Rutman, who=E2=80=99s president of Wi=
lloughby, joined Sculptor=E2=80=99s board in 2019 and served on the compens=
ation committee.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is=
 a story about Dan Och, who left Goldman to start a hedge fund called Och-Z=
iff Capital Management, which became one of the biggest hedge funds. It got=
 so big that he took the management company public in 2007, but it was so m=
uch his hedge fund that (1) his name was on it and (2) he <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26626731.270615/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3N=
qLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jbGFzaC1iZXR3ZWVuLWZvdW5kZXItYW5kLXByb3RlZ2UtcGx1bmdlcy=
1vY2gtemlmZi1pbnRvLWNyaXNpcy0xNTE2NzQzOTE2P21vZD1hcnRpY2xlX2lubGluZQ/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB06f21390" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">hired=C2=A0his children=E2=80=99s summ=
er-camp water-skiing instructor</a><em>=C2=A0</em>to be an investor at the =
fund. Really a classic =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s a pile of money with my name=
 on it=E2=80=9D move.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then throug=
h some combination of (1) Och being too rich to manage outside money full t=
ime, (2) the water-skiing instructor, Jimmy Levin, turning out to be by all=
 accounts an exceptionally talented (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/26626731.270615/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDctMjQvbHVja3ktaW52ZXN0b3JzLWFuZC12ZW5lenVlbGFuLWJ=
vbmRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDIwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcad06420" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">and lucky</a>) investor, (3) Levin=
 also apparently being rather a tough negotiator for himself and (4) public=
-company governance structures being somewhat less deferential to Och than =
a private pile of money would be, Och-Ziff became the more neutrally named =
Sculptor, Och left and Levin =E2=80=94=C2=A0after a power struggle in which=
 Och briefly installed someone else =E2=80=94=C2=A0became chief executive o=
fficer and chief investment officer.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Le=
vin is now in the unusual=C2=A0position of=C2=A0running a gigantic ($37.9 b=
illion) hedge fund without being the billionaire owner of, like, half the m=
oney in the=C2=A0fund. Instead he is the chief executive officer of a publi=
c hedge-fund firm with an equity market capitalization of about $1 billion,=
 who is paid mostly in management-company stock by a public company with a =
compensation committee of independent directors. CEOs of $1 billion market-=
cap firms, as a rule, do not get nine-digit pay packages. On the other hand=
 every year <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/266267=
31.270615/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctM=
DUtMTYvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZC1wYXktYW5kLXRyYWRlci1saWVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDcyMl9NT05F=
WVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI=
yMDIwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2684d2e4" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> we talk about=C2=A0rankings</a> of =E2=80=9Chighest paid hedge fun=
d managers,=E2=80=9D whose =E2=80=9Cpay=E2=80=9D (1) consists mostly of the=
 appreciation of their own stakes in their funds and (2) has 10 digits. As =
the CEO of a $1 billion public company, Levin is comically overpaid; as the=
=C2=A0manager of a $30+ billion hedge fund with good performance, he is get=
ting way, way, way less than his peers. Of course most of the people=C2=A0r=
unning $30+ billion hedge funds are running a lot of their own money, thoug=
h, which makes the comparison hard.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is=
 Rutman=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
26626731.270615/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDM=
yNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMDI3MTM5L2QzMDM0ODFkZXgxNzEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBe27cde60" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">letter of complaint</a>, which specifically cites tho=
se lists of =E2=80=9Chighest paid hedge fund managers=E2=80=9D as a source =
of Levin=E2=80=99s comp:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First,=
 the Compensation Committee recommended, and the Board approved, Mr. Levin=
=E2=80=99s compensation package despite Semler Brossy=E2=80=99s warning tha=
t even under a conservative =E2=80=9Cbase=E2=80=9D scenario, Mr. Levin woul=
d receive an =E2=80=9Camortized total compensation level of $94.3 million p=
er year, [which] is exceedingly rare across general industry=E2=80=9D and c=
ould only be deemed reasonable in the asset management industry if compared=
 to the annual gains of the world=E2=80=99s highest paid private alternativ=
e asset managers (much of which are likely to reflect the gains in their ow=
n investments in the funds, rather than Board-awarded compensation). =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deck distributed shortly in a=
dvance of the Board meeting reflects that the principal =E2=80=9Ccompetitiv=
e=E2=80=9D justification for the pay package was the representation that it=
 would =E2=80=9Censure competitive compensation within the private market h=
edge fund industry=E2=80=9D because the =E2=80=9C[t]op 25 hedge fund manage=
rs [have been] paid on average $200m to $2.7bn since 2009,=E2=80=9D and the=
 CIO of Blackrock=E2=80=99s hedge fund reportedly =E2=80=9Cearned a nine-fi=
gure sum,=E2=80=9D in the prior year.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">And:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, the Board a=
pproved an award of equity to Mr. Levin that would bring his pro-forma shar=
e/unit holdings to approximately 12.5 million shares/units, representing ap=
proximately 20.7 % of all outstanding shares. =E2=80=A6 The equity interest=
 in Sculptor that the Board has now granted Mr. Levin exceeds that of even =
the founders of asset management firms that are =E2=80=9Csignificantly larg=
er than Sculptor=E2=80=9D - - Apollo, Ares, Blackstone, and KKR. Of course,=
 Mr. Levin is not a founder of Sculptor and his significant equity stake is=
 the result of compensation awards, not his creation of the firm.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s all true but if they jus=
t gave him 100% of the equity in the management company he=E2=80=99d still =
be a little light compared to the other people running $30+ billion hedge f=
unds. Most of the people who have ended up in charge of $30+=C2=A0billion h=
edge funds will make a billion dollars if their fund has a good year, not b=
ecause a compensation committee voted them a billion-dollar paycheck but be=
cause they have, over the years of running the fund=C2=A0they founded, accr=
ued billions of dollars of investments in the fund, and when the fund goes =
up so does their wealth. If you bring in a new guy you have to either (1) g=
et him to accept a different model, one that involves him being much less r=
ich than the heads of competitor firms, or (2) throw tons of money at him t=
o catch him up.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" widt=
