3cB1b61c3a4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Financial Times reports</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse has securitised a portfolio of loans lin=
ked to its wealthiest customers=E2=80=99 yachts and private jets, in an unu=
sual use of derivatives to offload risks associated with lending to ultra-r=
ich oligarchs and entrepreneurs.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Swiss =
lender, which has endured a bruising year marked by repeated scandal, quiet=
ly sold on a slice of the risk related to $2bn of its =E2=80=9Cultra-high-n=
et-worth=E2=80=9D client loans at the end of 2021.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The securitisation of the portfolio of loans to tycoons and oligarc=
hs backed by their =E2=80=9Cjets, yachts, real estate and/or financial asse=
ts=E2=80=9D was made by a unit of the bank that has previously been plagued=
 with sanctions-related issues.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An investor=
 presentation for the deal, seen by the Financial Times, explains that one =
of the main goals of this division is to =E2=80=9Ccreate a positive brand i=
mpression of CS by financing the principals=E2=80=99 favourite business too=
ls (business jet) and luxury toys (yachts)=E2=80=9D. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The nature of the underlying collateral meant Credit S=
uisse had to offer an eye-watering interest rate of more than 11 per cent t=
o entice a handful of hedge funds into the $80mn transaction, an indication=
 of the price the bank was willing to pay to improve its capital position w=
ithout tapping public equity markets.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">One way to think about this is that if Credit Suisse is carving out=
 its oligarch yacht loans to sell their credit exposure to hedge funds, the=
n the hedge funds value the yacht loans more highly than public shareholder=
s do.[1] Like,=C2=A0you can go to hedge fund managers and say =E2=80=9Chey =
do you want to own the equity tranche of our oligarch yacht loans=E2=80=9D =
and the hedge fund managers will say =E2=80=9Cahahaha that=E2=80=99s awesom=
e I=E2=80=99m in for $10 million,=E2=80=9D and at the same time you can go =
to your regulators and shareholders and say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve moved th=
e oligarch yacht loans off our books, now if the oligarch yacht loans defau=
lt our shareholders and depositors will not be on the hook=E2=80=9D and the=
 shareholders and regulators will say =E2=80=9Cah what a relief, we don=E2=
=80=99t want any oligarch yacht loans.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The world of bank capital relief and significant risk transfer t=
rades can be pretty abstract, and I have written admiringly=C2=A0about Cred=
it Suisse=E2=80=99s efforts to make it more so. Credit Suisse has, among ot=
her things,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
6626731.270615/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFsYnJlYWtlci5jb20vMjAxMi8wNC9tYXJ2ZWwtYXQtdGhl=
